english:
  title: In Praise of the Vairocana Buddha Image
  author: Byeon Gyeryang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The consort grieves for Prince Sho-gyeong, now gone.
    She offers forth his robes and treasured things,
    commissioning a painting of the Western Assembly,
    and a sacred image too—Shakyamuni and Vairocana both.

    Hung in the temple near the burial mound,
    incense coils daily, lamplight burns morning and night,
    the altar fresh with flowers.

    Alas, what great vow the consort has made:
    to cultivate merit for the departed soul,
    to plant seeds of virtue in the unseen realm.

    Yet sentient beings and Buddha are not two things—
    how then could compassion not respond and shine forth clear?
    Why speak only of separation's sting?

    With resolve unshaken, the eye beholds
    the luminous body, pure and free.
  footnotes:
    - Vairocana (毗盧) represents the cosmic Buddha of ultimate reality; Shakyamuni is the historical Buddha. Together they embody different aspects of enlightenment.
    - The Western Assembly refers to Amitabha Buddha's Pure Land, a central image in East Asian Buddhist devotion.
    - The 'luminous body' (清淨身) in the final line refers to Buddha's transcendent form, suggesting the consort's spiritual vision achieved through this merit-making.
